Flow probes and PC-CMR were used to acquire flow measurements into and out of the LV. The volume of the ventricle as a function of time was calculated from each of these modalities and was compared to the values obtained from SP and CMR respectively (Fig. 9). It was found that the average discrepancy (across the cardiac cycle) between SP and the flow probes was 5.9 ± 4.1 % while that between CMR and PC-CMR was found to be 8 ± 6 %. Figure 10 compares the normalized volume of the LV calculated from CMR and SP. The qualitative trends through the cardiac cycle were similar. The mean discrepancy between CMR and SP was 5.5 ± 3.7 % while the largest discrepancy throughout the entire cardiac cycle was approximately 14 %, occurring during peak diastole and peak systole.Fig. 9
